hands_on_practices.solution:
1. Hölder's inequality in ℝ³ with exponents $p$ and $q$ (conjugate: $1/p+1/q=1$) gives
$$\mathbf a\cdot\mathbf b\le\|\mathbf a\|_p\;\|\mathbf b\|_q.$$

2. Here $p=\tfrac{4}{3}$, so
$$\frac{1}{p}+\frac{1}{q}=1\;\Longrightarrow\;\frac{3}{4}+\frac{1}{q}=1
\;\Longrightarrow\;\frac{1}{q}=\frac{1}{4}\;\Longrightarrow\;q=4.$$

3. Compute $\|\mathbf a\|_{4/3}$:
$$\|\mathbf a\|_{4/3}
=\Bigl(|1|^{4/3}+|2|^{4/3}+|3|^{4/3}\Bigr)^{\frac{3}{4}}
=\bigl(1+2^{\tfrac{4}{3}}+3^{\tfrac{4}{3}}\bigr)^{\tfrac{3}{4}}.$$

4. Compute $\|\mathbf b\|_{4}$:
$$\|\mathbf b\|_{4}
=\bigl(4^4+5^4+6^4\bigr)^{\frac{1}{4}}
=\bigl(256+625+1296\bigr)^{\frac{1}{4}}
=2177^{\frac{1}{4}}.$$

5. Therefore the Hölder bound is
$$\|\mathbf a\|_{4/3}\,\|\mathbf b\|_{4}
=\bigl(1+2^{\tfrac{4}{3}}+3^{\tfrac{4}{3}}\bigr)^{\tfrac{3}{4}}
\;2177^{\tfrac{1}{4}}.$$
